ish: variant of   Jeffries  ."]},{"name":"Jeffress","meanings":["English (Durham): variant of   Jeffries  ."]},{"name":"Jefferis","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire, Wiltshire, and Hampshire): variant of   Jeffries  ."]},{"name":"Jefferys","meanings":["English: variant of   Jeffries  ."]},{"name":"Jeffreys","meanings":["English: variant of   Jeffries  ."]},{"name":"Jeffers","meanings":["English: variant of   Jeffries  . This form of the surname is strongly associated with Ireland."]},{"name":"Jeffrey","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the common Middle English and Older Scots personal name <i>Geffrey</i>, a borrowing of Old French <i>Geuffrei</i>, <i>Jeufrei</i>, <i>Jefrei</i>, <i>Gosfrei</i>, <i>Jofrei</i>. The principal source of the Old French forms was probably ancient Germanic <i>Gautfrid</i>, from an ethnic name + <i>frithu</i> ‘peace’. It was commonly Latinized in early documents as <i>Gaufridus</i> or <i>Galfridus</i>, but also as <i>Goisfridus</i> or <i>Gosfridus</i>. Anglo-Norman French <i>Jofreith</i>, <i>Jofrei</i> lies behind the English surnames <i>Joffrey</i> and <i>Joffray</i>, which are recorded in the late nineteenth century, but may now be extinct."]}]},{"name":"Joanna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form, <i>Io(h)anna</i>, of Greek <i>Iōanna</i>, the feminine equivalent of <i>Iōannēs</i> (  see  John  ). In the New Testament, this name is borne by a woman who was one of Jesus's followers (Luke 8:3; 24:10). She was the wife of the steward of the household of King Herod Antipas. The name was regularly used throughout the Middle Ages in most parts of Europe as a feminine equivalent of   John  , but in England it has only been in common use as a vernacular given name since the 19th century. Celebrated British bearers of the name include the novelist  Joanna Trollope  (  b. 1943 ), the actress  Joanna Lumley  (  b. 1946 ), and the concert pianist  Joanna McGregor  (  b. 1959 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Joannah","meanings":["From the Latin form, <i>Io(h)anna</i>, of Greek <i>Iōanna</i>, the feminine equivalent of <i>Iōannēs</i> (  see  John  ). In the New Testament, this name is borne by a woman who was one of Jesus's followers (Luke 8:3; 24:10). She was the wife of the steward of the household of King Herod Antipas. The name was regularly used throughout the Middle Ages in most parts of Europe as a feminine equivalent of   John  , but in England it has only been in common use as a vernacular given name since the 19th century. Celebrated British bearers of the name include the novelist  Joanna Trollope  (  b. 1943 ), the actress  Joanna Lumley  (  b. 1946 ), and the concert pianist  Joanna McGregor  (  b. 1959 )."]},{"name":"Joana","meanings":["From the Latin form, <i>Io(h)anna</i>, of Greek <i>Iōanna</i>, the feminine equivalent of <i>Iōannēs</i> (  see  John  ). In the New Testament, this name is borne by a woman who was one of Jesus's followers (Luke 8:3; 24:10). She was the wife of the steward of the household of King Herod Antipas. The name was regularly used throughout the Middle Ages in most parts of Europe as a feminine equivalent of   John  , but in England it has only been in common use as a vernacular given name since the 19th century. Celebrated British bearers of the name include the novelist  Joanna Trollope  (  b. 1943 ), the actress  Joanna Lumley  (  b. 1946 ), and the concert pianist  Joanna McGregor  (  b. 1959 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":20,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705201,"age":114,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Joanna Jeffries was born in 1435, in Kelvedon Hatch, Essex, England as the daughter of Jeffries. She married Richard de Ville. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1435–":"1435–Surnud","1435–Female":"1435–Surnud","1430–Male":"1430–Surnud","1452–1509":"1452–1509","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1452":"1452","1430":"1430","1509":"1509","1549":"1549","Kelvedon Hatch, Essex, England":"Kelvedon Hatch, Essex, England","Dagenham, London Borough of Barking and Dagenham, Greater London, England":"Dagenham, London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1435–":"1435–Kuollut","1435–Female":"1435–Kuollut","1430–Male":"1430–Kuollut","1452–1509":"1452–1509","1410–Male":"1410–Kuollut","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1452":"1452","1430":"1430","1509":"1509","1549":"1549","Kelvedon Hatch, Essex, England":"Kelvedon Hatch, Essex, England","Dagenham, London Borough of Barking and Dagenham, Greater London, England":"Dagenham, London, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1435–":"1435–Décédée","1435–Female":"1435–Décédée","1430–Male":"1430–Décédé","1452–1509":"1452–1509","1410–Male":"1410–Décédé","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1452":"1452","1430":"1430","1509":"1509","1549":"1549","Kelvedon Hatch, Essex, England":"Kelvedon Ha